title: psort fail to export dfdatetime.DateTimeValues to json and OpenSearch

labels.name: output
labels.description: Output modules and output process

body:
**Description of problem:**

Psort fail to export in json values of type `dfdatetime.DateTimeValues` when the value is an attribute of an event (eg. previous_run_times in [winprefetch](https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/53f532a3e066dc0269aa7e748737b4c50944abc4/plaso/parsers/winprefetch.py#L27)

For opensearch no crashes occur but the bulk export fails if the bulk contains an event that could not be serialized.

**Command line and arguments:**

```
log2timeline.py --partition all --hashers sha1  ~/Downloads/HP-Final/Laptop1Final.E01
# jsonl
./psort.py -o json_line -w fail.jsonl 20221228T162736-Laptop1Final.E01.plaso  "parser is 'prefetch' and timestamp_desc is not 'Creation Time'" 
# opensearch
./psort.py -o opensearch --opensearch-user admin --opensearch-server "localhost" --use_ssl --opensearch-port 9200 20221228T162736-Laptop1Final.E01.plaso "parser is 'prefetch'"
```

**Source data:**

https://cfreds.nist.gov/all/MagnetForensics/2022WindowsMagnetCTF (but any windows image with prefetch should cause the crash).

**Plaso version:**

20221227

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

Tested on MacOS and Ubuntu 20.04

**Installation method:**

* manually (pip from source)

title: No prompt for volume shadow copies.

labels.name: UX
labels.description: Issues related to user experience

labels.name: tools
labels.description: Issue related to the tools

body:
**Description of problem:**
I can no longer get log2timeline to prompt for which volume shadow copies (VSCs) I want to timeline. When log2timeline is run on a partition with VSCs and I don't specify any VSS options (i.e., --no_vss, --vss_only, --vss_stores), log2timeline no longer prompts for VSCs to be selected. Please note, the --unattended option is not used. The following tests were conducted.

- The command line (provided below) was run against two different E01 images. 
- The E01 images were mounted with Arsenal Image Mounter, and this tool verifies that VSCs do exist on the OS partition.
-  `vssadmin list shadows` was also run to confirm the existence of the VSCs
-  log2timeline was run with the `--vss_stores all` option, and it timelines the VSCs as expected.
-  The same idea was tested with the `--partitions` option. When I omit this option, I am prompted to select a partition as expected.

**Command line and arguments:**
`log2timeline.py --status_view window  --file_filter filter_no_winsxs.yaml  --log-file ./myfolder/mylog.txt --storage-file ./myfolder/mystorage.plaso ./myfolder/mysourcedata.e01`

`log2timeline.py --status_view window --partitions all --file_filter filter_no_winsxs.yaml  --log-file ./myfolder/mylog.txt --storage-file ./myfolder/mystorage.plaso ./myfolder/mysourcedata.e01`

**Source data:**
I am unable to share the source data.

**Plaso version:**
20210606

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**
Ubuntu 20.04

**Installation method:**
From the official documentation for Ubuntu 20.04
https://plaso.readthedocs.io/en/latest/sources/user/Ubuntu-Packaged-Release.html

**Debug output/tracebacks:**
Conversation with joachimmetz in Slack indicated a potential issue with:
https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/main/plaso/cli/storage_media_tool.py#L621

*Expected behavior*: Timezone information is consistent between the different output formats.

Note that the timestamps in the `dynamic` output are all over the place regarding time shifts and the given timezones are incorrent. Nonetheless, the correct order of the entries is preserverd. Something similar can be observed for `l2tcsv` output.


**Command line and arguments:**

Command to generate the plaso file from source data:
```
docker run -v "$PWD:/data" --rm -it log2timeline/plaso log2timeline --parsers=linux,apache_access --file-filter=/data/filter.txt --partitions 1 --storage_file /data/server.plaso /data/server.E01
```

Command to generate the `xlsx` output:
```
docker run -v "$PWD:/data" --rm -it log2timeline/plaso psort -o xlsx -w /data/server.xlsx /data/server.plaso 'date > DATETIME("2021-06-30T11:30:00+02:00")' 
```
```

```

**Source data:**

I can provide this to anyone interested. Just an E01 of a fairly minimal Debian 10 instatllation with LAMP stack and Wordpress for testing purposes.

Current version from Docker Hub:
```
$ docker run --rm -it log2timeline/plaso log2timeline --version
plaso - log2timeline version 20210606
```

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

Whatever the container uses internally, Docker host is Debian Sid.

**Installation method:**

Docker.

**Debug output/tracebacks:**

Nothing meaningful in both debug and log output of `psort`.

title: log2timeline does not enable all parser plugins unless the plugin list is explicitly specified

labels.name: core
labels.description: Issues relating to Plaso's core - processing, file access etc.

labels.name: parsers
labels.description: Issues related to parsers and parser plug-ins

body:
For example, `win7_slow` includes `esedb`, but `esedb/srum` will not be used.

The problem is inconsistency in [`ParsersManager.GetParserObjects`](https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/030db76c23fcdabd7462f37924f724d34ee66b67/plaso/parsers/manager.py#L237):
- [ `ParserFilterExpressionHelper.SplitExpression`](https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/030db76c23fcdabd7462f37924f724d34ee66b67/plaso/filters/parser_filter.py#L194) uses an asterisk character ('*') to represet all plugins
- [`BaseParser.EnablePlugins`](https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/030db76c23fcdabd7462f37924f724d34ee66b67/plaso/parsers/interface.py#L112) expects that None or an empty list represents all plugins.

title: Datetime not properly adjusted with timezone for syslog parser

labels.name: parsers

**Description of problem:**

When using the syslog plugin, I found a discrepancy between two systems that pointed me to a potential timezone bug in log2timeline.

The two analyzed system images are mounted in Linux before being parsed with log2timeline.py (instead of parsing a raw image).

Running pinfo.py shows proper detection of the timezone even if the analyzed system has been mounted in /mnt: CET for system1, UTC for system2.

However if I look at an arbitrary syslog event on the system1, psort output the event with the same timestamp than the original syslog entry (traditionnal syslog entry), showing that the datetime has not been adjusted to UTC.

title: pinfo running working in Docker is passed unsupported unattended option

labels.name: deployment
labels.description: Changes to deployment or development utility scripts

body:
Hi,

When using the docker image, pinfo returns an error:
"pinfo.py: error: unrecognized arguments: --unattended"

command:
$ docker run log2timeline/plaso pinfo

In fact, when running pinfo.py in the container, it works well:
$ docker run -it -v /my/folder:/data_dest --entrypoint /bin/bash log2timeline/plaso
then:
pinfo.py /data_dest/disk.plaso

Looking at /usr/local/bin/plaso-switch.sh, it seems there is a typo in pinfo switch case, and the command does not support the option '--unattended'.

Best Regards

--vss_stores parameter value format unclear

**Description of problem:**

title: L2T worker exceeds 2GB cap, kills worker and then spins off more workers than defined at CML until proces hangs.

labels.name: core
labels.description: Issues relating to Plaso's core - processing, file access etc.

labels.name: parsers
labels.description: Issues related to parsers and parser plug-ins

body:
**Description of problem:**

Log2Timeline chokes on a specific VSS artifact, kills worker and spins up much more workers than defined at command line. System crashes after memory fills up to max. 

**Command line and arguments:**

`log2timeline.py --workers 4 --status_view window --logfile /data/l2t_!PRIVACY!.log /data/!PRIVACY!.plaso /data/Evidence/!Privacy!.E01`

**Source data:**

Microsoft Windows based E01 Image File with multiple partitions and one VSS. Image is stored at a Windows based Samba fileshare and dir of located E01 image file is mounted using Cifs Utils on 18.04 Ubuntu server. This mount is mounted again in Plaso Docker container.

**Plaso version:**

20190331

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

Docker based Plaso instance pulled from Docker hub. Docker is running on Ubuntu 18.04 Bionic

**Installation method:**

Docker based Plaso instance pulled from Docker hub. Docker is running on Ubuntu 18.04 Bionic

title: Duplicated events with incorrect timestamp
body:
**Description of problem:**

In the last version of Plaso, we are seeing certain events being duplicated with a wrong timestamp, that might lead an investigator to wrong assumptions. The problem *seems* related only to evtx parsing. Here's an example with anonymized data:

20180127 version. The real event is the one from `2018-02-07T12:04:26+00:00`, all the others never happened:
```
[user@server] $ cat latest.csv | grep -i inject
2017-12-22T09:43:47.125000+00:00,Content Modification Time,EVT,WinEVTX,[258 / 0x0102] Source Name: MyAVEvent Strings: ['The file c:\Documents and Settings\InnocentUser\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Low\Content.IE5\73YTJFYZ\inject[1].js contains  Trojan.   Record Number: 29731 Event Level: 3,winevtx,OS:/somewhere/evtxlogs/application.evtx,-
2018-01-16T12:57:07.915036+00:00,Content Modification Time,EVT,WinEVTX,[258 / 0x0102] Source Name: MyAVEvent Strings: ['The file c:\Documents and Settings\InnocentUser\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Low\Content.IE5\73YTJFYZ\inject[1].js contains  Trojan.   Record Number: 29731 Event Level: 3,winevtx,OS:/somewhere/evtxlogs/application.evtx,-
2018-01-29T15:07:34+00:00,Content Modification Time,EVT,WinEVTX,[258 / 0x0102] Source Name: MyAVEvent Strings: ['The file c:\Documents and Settings\InnocentUser\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Low\Content.IE5\73YTJFYZ\inject[1].js contains  Trojan.   Record Number: 29731 Event Level: 3,winevtx,OS:/somewhere/evtxlogs/application.evtx,-
2018-02-07T12:04:26+00:00,Content Modification Time,EVT,WinEVTX,[258 / 0x0102] Source Name: MyAVEvent Strings: ['The file c:\Documents and Settings\InnocentUser\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Low\Content.IE5\73YTJFYZ\inject[1].js contains  Trojan.   Record Number: 29731 Event Level: 3,winevtx,OS:/somewhere/evtxlogs/application.evtx,-
2018-02-13T16:02:30.934406+00:00,Content Modification Time,EVT,WinEVTX,[258 / 0x0102] Source Name: MyAVEvent Strings: ['The file c:\Documents and Settings\InnocentUser\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Low\Content.IE5\73YTJFYZ\inject[1].js contains  Trojan.   Record Number: 29731 Event Level: 3,winevtx,OS:/somewhere/evtxlogs/application.evtx,-
```

20171231 version. This is correct.
```
[user@server] $ cat 311217.csv | grep inject
2018-02-07T12:04:26+00:00,Content Modification Time,EVT,WinEVTX,[258 / 0x0102] Source Name: MyAVEvent Strings: ['The file c:\Documents and Settings\InnocentUser\AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows\Temporary Internet Files\Low\Content.IE5\73YTJFYZ\inject[1].js contains  Trojan.  Record Number: 29731 Event Level: 3,winevtx,OS:/somewhere/evtxlogs/application.evtx,-
```

The `create.log` file contains parsing error in both the cases:
`Number of errors encountered while extracting events: XY`.

However, this doesn't look relevant, as the amount of errors is the same in both the cases.

**Command line and arguments:**
Plaso runs in a docker image based on ubuntu 16:04
The relevant command line for log2timeline is the following:

`log2timeline --status_view linear /path/file.plaso /path/evtxlogs/whatever.evtx`


**Source data:**

Unfortunately I can't provide this.

**Plaso version:**

The bug affects  20180127. 

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

Docker container based on Ubuntu 16:04.

**Installation method:**

From dockerfile:
```
RUN add-apt-repository -y "deb http://ppa.launchpad.net/gift/stable/ubuntu xenial main"
```

**Debug output/tracebacks:**

Please let me know if the data I've provided it's enough to start an investigation. If you need more logs, I need to anonymize them before providing.

Thanks

title: Queued tasks not correctly timed out

labels.name: core
labels.description: Issues relating to Plaso's core - processing, file access etc.

body:
In the task manager, HasPendingTasks checks for TasksPendingRetry https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/multi_processing/task_manager.py#L297 before attempting to time out tasks that are queued https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/multi_processing/task_manager.py#L303.

HasTasksPendingRetry checks for abandoned tasks that haven't been retried https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/multi_processing/task_manager.py#L333 while GetRetryTask (correctly) checks for abandoned tasks that haven't been retried and are not themselves retries of an abandoned task https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/multi_processing/task_manager.py#L347

This leads to tasks that have been queued, picked up by a worker, and then abandoned never being timed out, while the engine continues to be told by the manager that there are still tasks being processed by workers.

When you change the default text format to markdown for pinfo I discovered an issue when markdown prints rows. *(btw, I suggest adding the ability to select markdown in pinfo)*

```python
File "D:\dev\plaso\tools\pinfo.py", line 589, in PrintStorageInformation
  self._PrintStorageInformation(storage_file)

  output_writer.Write(u' | '.join(values))

```python
values = [u'{0!s}'.format(value) for value in values]
```

title: Missing sleep time during opening of gzip storage file.
body:
plaso.storage.gzip_file module is missing sleep time during open (https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/storage/gzip_file.py#L320) which is sometimes causing IOErrors when running psort with analysis plugins (on Windows).

It should have:
```python
 time.sleep(self._LOCKED_FILE_SLEEP_TIME)
```
similar to merge function: https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/storage/gzip_file.py#L425

body:
**Plaso version:**
1.5.1 Release

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**
openSUSE 42.1 64-bit

**Installation method:**
Installed Plaso from source using python virtualenv, described here: https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/wiki/running-plaso-in-virtualenv

**Description of problem:**
I tested the new release (v1.5.1) using the evidence images from SANS FOR508 and I have experienced inconsistent results when compared to results generated by v1.5.0, as seen in the attached text files.

For example, using the nfury image Plaso (log2timeline) v1.5.0 and v1.5.1 both correctly identify the operating system (Windows 7 Ent 64-bit). Both versions also enable most of the same parsers and plugins, yet the results are dramatically different. Plaso v1.5.0 produces 1451110 total events while Plaso v1.5.1 produces 38918 total events. There are other differences as well, such as errors. For my tests, I ran log2timeline using the "kitchen sink" approach, with and without VSS selected.
`e.g., log2timeline.py nfury.dump nfury.E01`

I also tried the nfury image on a second system (Ubuntu 16.04 in VMware WS) using both Plaso v1.5.0 and Plaso v1.5.1 and got the same results.

If needed, I have 5 dump files from Plaso v1.5.1 which I could share. They average between 2.4 MB and 3.2 MB each. I could also run pinfo against any/all of the dump files I created if you need more examples for comparison.

If you'd like me to try anything else, let me know. I'd be happy to help.

Chris

**Description of problem:**

I have been using the `nsrlsvr` analysis as well as the `tagging` analysis plugin. Both plugins tag events. After running both analysis plugins, tags from both plugins end up in the `event_tag_data` files in the dump file.

A single tag is set in line 1565 of `storage/zip_file.py`: 

```
event.tag = self._ReadEventTagByIdentifier(event.store_number, event.store_index, event.uuid)
```

Apart from the assignment there, `_ReadEventTagByIdentifier` itself would also need changes. In this function, a tag is retrieved by using `event_uuid` as a reference. More than one tag could be available with that reference though, so which tag would need to be read by the function is ambiguous.

response = nsrl_socket.recv(self._RECEIVE_BUFFER_SIZE).rstrip()

title: Analysis plugin nsrlsvr: KeyError in plaso/analysis/interface.py

labels.name: analysis
labels.description: Issue related to analysis plugins

milestone.title: 1.5.1 release
milestone.description: Bugfix release for 1.5.1

body:
**Plaso version:**

1.5.0 Release

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

XUbuntu 64 bit

**Installation method:**

Installed from GiFT

**Description of problem:**

Tagging events using the `--analysis nsrlsvr` option throws an exception. 

**Debug output/tracebacks:**

The following error is shown in the debug log:

```
[ERROR] (nsrlsvr   ) PID:XXXXX <analysis_process> <dfvfs.path.os_path_spec.OSPathSpec object at 0xXXXXXXXXXXXX>
Traceback (most recent call last):                                                                                                     
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/plaso/multi_processing/analysis_process.py", line 138, in _Main                               
    self._analysis_mediator.ProduceAnalysisReport(self._analysis_plugin)                                                               
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/plaso/analysis/mediator.py", line 95, in ProduceAnalysisReport                                
    analysis_report = plugin.CompileReport(self)                                                                                       
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/plaso/analysis/interface.py", line 280, in CompileReport                                      
    hash_analysis)                                                                                                                     
  File "/usr/lib/python2.7/dist-packages/plaso/analysis/interface.py", line 187, in _HandleHashAnalysis                                
    event_uuids = self._event_uuids_by_pathspec.pop(pathspec)                                                                          
KeyError: <dfvfs.path.os_path_spec.OSPathSpec object at 0xXXXXXXXXXXXX>
```

**Source data:**

The exception is caused by popping from `_event_uuids_by_pathspec`. This is a `defaultdict`, so retrieving an unexisting entry from the dict using the key would be no problem. A `pop()` is, though. 

Problem can be fixed by catching a KeyError on line 187 of `plaso/analysis/interface.py` and set `event_uuids` to an empty list.

```
  try:
    event_uuids = self._event_uuids_by_pathspec.pop(pathspec)
  except KeyError:
    event_uuids = []
```

title: Tagging output incorrect
body:
**Plaso version:**

1.5.0 Release

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

XUbuntu 64 bit

**Installation method:**

Installed from GiFT

**Description of problem:**

Tagging events using the `--analysis tagging` option works fine. When writing the events to output though, incorrect tag labels are written. The correct events are tagged with a label, but the label value is set to the first label written.

Let's say that we have event 1, 2 and 3. We have a tagging file which contains rules to tag event 1 with label 'one', and tag event 3 with label 'three'. After using the tagging option, the storage file contains correct labels for events 1 and 3. When using an output option (like `-o l2tcsv` or `-o json_line` for instance), the output contains label 'one' for both events 1 and 3. Event 2 is written without a tag.

**Source data:**

Problem can be fixed in `plaso/storage/zip_file.py` : on line 1831, replace `tag_index_value.store_index` with `tag_index_value.offset` .

title: Syslog parser cannot parse non-ASCII log messages

labels.name: parsers
labels.description: Issues related to parsers and parser plug-ins

body:
**Plaso version:**

1.5RC

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

Ubuntu 16.04LTS

**Installation method:**

ppa:gift/dev

**Description of problem:**

Syslog parser uses ascii codec and therefore cannot parse syslog messages encoded in UTF8.

```
*********************************** Error: 3 ***********************************
           Message : Unable to read lines from file with error: 'ascii' codec
                     can't decode byte 0xc2 in position 112: ordinal not in
                     range(128)
      Parser chain : syslog
Path specification : type: OS, location: /home/Dev/ntfs.dd
                   : type: RAW
                   : type: TSK, inode: 3426, location: /log/syslog.1
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
```

This syslog entry was generated by an Ubuntu 16.04LTS machine with locale set to en_NZ.  

An improvement would be to switch to utf8, a superset of ascii and a very common codec.

Perhaps the ultimate (future) solution would be to adapt the codec depending on system locale, and/or try other codecs in the event of this error.

title: SQLite error: file is encrypted or not a database

labels.name: duplicate
labels.description: Duplicate of another issue

body:
**Plaso version:**

https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/commit/ebe1a0e0822587fbbb7cfd3d2233b8d763aafe27

**Operating system Plaso is running on:**

Windows 7

**Installation method:**

Development environment.

**Description of problem:**

I'm getting a "file is encrypted or not a database" error when I try to parse sqlite files. 

**Solution:**

This is being caused by the file_object being at offset 24 instead of 0 when the database is opened.
This can be fixed by adding 

``` python
file_object.seek(0)
```

after line:  https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/parsers/sqlite.py#L346

This was caused because of the incorrect assumption that "GetFileObject()" returns a file_object offset at 0.

title: Workers Idle on CryptnetCacheUrl files

labels.name: core
labels.description: Issues relating to Plaso's core - processing, file access etc.

body:
Plaso 1.4 release

Running on Ubuntu 14.04.   

Installed via SANS SIFT installer script

Scenario:
Analying a Windows 7 raw image, taken with DD.   Tested log2timeline with default options on both the raw DD by providing an offset, as well as with the image mounted to a directory.

Problem:  
Workers hang and then perma-sleep on files within CryptnetCacheUrl directories of user profiles as well as in Windows/ServiceProfiles, eventually causing the "Idle too long" feature to kick in and stop log2timeline.   I attemted running log2timeline with root privileges just in case, but it didn't help.

This failure was occurring towards the end of a run on a 500GB drive, so to test it I re-ran log2timeline against one of the specific folders I know it was having trouble with, Windows/ServiceProfiles/LocalService/AppData/LocalLow/Microsoft/CryptnetUrlCache/
These CryptnetUrlCache folders also exist in each user's profile, within the same AppData folder structure.   

Debug log:
[test.txt](https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/files/311995/test.txt)

This appears to be similar in nature to #589

title: RE in plaso/engine/worker.py to identify Chrome cache files is incorrect

labels.name: core
labels.description: Issues relating to Plaso's core - processing, file access etc.

body:
The regular expression at https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/engine/worker.py#L69 that is intended to identify Chrome cache files is incorrect.

This problem was introduced on 26 December 2015 here: https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/pull/468

The RE currently reads:

_CHROME_CACHE_DATA_FILE_RE = re.compile(r'^[fF]_[0-9]{6}$')

This incorrectly assumes that Chrome cache files contain a sequence of six decimal digits, when the digits can be hexadecimal.  Therefore cache files with names like ...

/Users/XXXX/AppData/Local/Google/Chrome/User Data/Default/Cache/f_00002a

... do not match the RE test in _CanSkipContentExtraction() leading _CanSkipContentExtraction() to return False instead of True.  

The workers then become clogged up with gzip extraction which takes a long time, leading to an abort due to workers being idle for too long.

Problem occurs in 1.4.0 release and git repo code as of 20160414 (yes I have updated my dependancies).

Changing the RE to:

  _CHROME_CACHE_DATA_FILE_RE = re.compile(r'^[fF]_[0-9a-fA-F]{6}$')

(note the added "a-fA-F")

... fixed the problem and allowed the image I was working on to complete processing successfully.

Detailed debugging info (screenshots, logs with debug enabled, etc) is available but does not seem necessary for a such a straightforward fix.

labels.description: Issues relating to Plaso's core - processing, file access etc.

body:
There is no way filter by individual plugins. Whenever I attempt to filter by a single plugin it runs all of the parent parser's plugins.

For example, the following will run all of the sqlite_plugins:

> log2timeline.py C:\Output C:\Input --parsers sqlite,-sqlite/appusage
> log2timeline.py C:\Output C:\Input --parsers appusage

Also the following commands will run no parsers at all.

> log2timeline.py C:\Output C:\Input --parsers sqlite/appusage
> log2timeline.py C:\Output C:\Input --parsers sqlite,-appusage 

I am not sure if this is the intended behavior. This is a similar issue to #125

title: Processing ends prematurely when using ZeroMQ and a low number of workers (or slow I/O)

labels.name: core
labels.description: Issues relating to Plaso's core - processing, file access etc.

body:
The ZeroMQ queue timeout for the storage writer's event queue is 60 seconds, so if workers get stuck for a while without producing events (due to hashing a large file, slow I/O etc.) the storage writer can timeout, assume the workers are dead, and exit.

This problem is not readily apparent when there are large numbers of workers, as there's less chance for all the workers stalling at the same time.

Bug privately reported. 

The cups_ipp parser produces events with raw string values. These occasionally contain invalid unicode values, eg.

 'date-time-at-completed': ['\x07\xdf....

The parser uses construct.PascalString() and puts the output directly into the events. Strings produced by PascalString() are raw, not unicode.

title: incorrect paths in filter_windows.txt
body:
Running image_export against a Windows 7 Home Premium image, I get the follow:

[INFO] [PreProcess] Set attribute: sysregistry to /Windows/System32/config
[INFO] [PreProcess] Set attribute: systemroot to /Windows
[INFO] [PreProcess] Set attribute: windir to /Windows

filter_windows.txt tries to collect {systemroot}/winevt/Logs/.+[.]evtx

Changing this to {systemroot}/System32/winevt/Logs/.+[.]evtx resolves the issue.

Not sure if this is an error in the filter file or if systemroot is incorrectly set.

title: Unicode decode errors handling command line arguments

labels.name: dependency
labels.description: Issues related to, or caused by a dependency

body:
Running log2timeline.py on images containing non-ascii characters on the latest SIFT workstation gives me the above error message. Also tested on latest version pulled from github.

A quick google search took me to (http://stackoverflow.com/questions/22947181/dont-argparse-read-unicode-from-commandline) where a similar issue is discussed.

A search and replace for 5 instances of "type=unicode" with "type=lambda s: s.decode(sys.getfilesystemencoding())" in log2timeline.py appears to resolve the issue for me:

sed -ri 's/type=unicode/type=lambda s: s.decode(sys.getfilesystemencoding())/' log2timeline.py

title: Running tool in single process with debug does not envoke pdb shell

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: New or improved functionality

body:
Running the tool (log2timeline) in single process mode with debug turned on does not get the tool to drop into a pdb session anymore.

Instead of the error handler in the extraction frontend handling the exception the worker catches it:
https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/engine/worker.py#L487

``` python
    # All exceptions need to be caught here to prevent the worker
    # form being killed by an uncaught exception.
    except Exception as exception:
      logging.warning(
          u'Unhandled exception while processing path spec: {0:s}.'.format(
              path_spec.comparable))
      logging.exception(exception)
```

This effectively means that the worker has already caught the exception and logged it before it reaches the extraction front-end, thus not evoking the pdb debug shell.

Adding `raise` there causes multiprocessing to fail since there isn't a good handler for it. The worker ATM does not know whether or not it is being run as a single process or multi process.

There needs to be some sort of signal to the worker that it should present a debug shell if catching an un-handled exception and that signal should be sent to the worker in the case where the tool is run under single process and with debug turned on.

title: IIS Parser fails when log lines don't have date or time column.

labels.name: parsers
labels.description: Issues related to parsers and parser plug-ins

body:
Right now, if the log line in the parser does not have a date or time column, the IIS parser will produce the "Unable to extract timestamp from IIS log line" error at line (203) and will continue to produce this error for every line in the file. 

One solution would be to not have the parser parse the file if the date or time column is missing from the Fields line. This would improve speed, however we can be missing valuable information.

Another solution is to use the date and/or time from the "#Date:" line in the header if one of the respective columns doesn't exist. We then perhaps change the `timestamp_desc` when this situation occurs.

title: storage: zipfile open fails on some implementations due to negative seek

labels.name: obsolete
labels.description: Issue that is no longer relevant

body:
On some implementations the [append mode](https://github.com/log2timeline/plaso/blob/master/plaso/lib/storage.py#L297) seems to cause zipfile to make a negative seek (before 0), strictly speaking this is non-POSIX compliant behavior.

From man lseek:

```
EINVAL whence is not valid.  Or: the resulting file offset would be negative, or beyond the end of a seekable device.
```

Work around is to use write mode if the zip file does not exists, however we cannot rely on os.path.exists() to determine if the file exists.

title: Issues with path detection for the Windows Event signature database

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: New or improved functionality

body:
Running plaso in virtualenv, I parse a disk image

```
$ log2timeline.py /tmp/foo.dump evil.dd
```

And then run psort in the following way:

```
$ psort.py /tmp/foo.dump "parser contains 'evt'"
```

Get a traceback:
    Traceback (most recent call last):
    ...
    File "/plaso_playground/virtual/local/lib/python2.7/site-packages/plaso-1.2.1_20150318-py2.7.egg/plaso/formatters/winevt_rc.py", line 82, in GetValues
    raise RuntimeError(u'Cannot retrieve values database not opened.')
    RuntimeError: Cannot retrieve values database not opened.

Run the tool in debug mode to get the exact location where the tool auto-detects the location of the database:

```
$ psort.py /tmp/foo.dump "parser contains 'evt'" -d
```

This results in the crash and the following pdb session:

```
(Pdb) self.filename
u'/test/plaso_playground/virtual/share/plaso/winevt-rc.db'
(Pdb) !import os
(Pdb) !os.path.isfile(self.filename)
False
```

I then go check and see that the file is actually here:
/test/plaso_playground/virtual/lib/python2.7/site-packages/plaso-1.2.1_20150318-py2.7.egg/share/plaso/winevt-rc.db

That is the location for the file is wrongly calculated.... or the database file is not properly copied over to the appropriate location....

title: Parser selection behavior is not adequately defined
body: Parser selection is only based on the parser name, if you have a plugin, like "firefox_history" the actual parser "sqlite" does not get chosen as part of the included parsers.

title: Infinite Loop: Terminating Worker - Worker is still Alive

labels.name: duplicate
labels.description: Duplicate of another issue

body:

title: Issues with the Chrome Preferences parser
body:
While parsing a test disk image:

```
2015-01-21 14:12:27,699 [WARNING] (Worker_1  ) PID:731 <worker> [chrome_preferences] Unable to process file: type: OS, location: /PATHtest_images/win7-64-nfury-10.3.58.6/win7-64-nfury-c-drive/win7-64-nfury-c-drive.E01
type: EWF
type: TSK, inode: 80707, location: /Users/nfury/AppData/Local/Google/Chrome/User Data/Default/Preferences
 with error: int() can't convert non-string with explicit base.

2015-01-21 14:12:27,699 [ERROR] (Worker_1  ) PID:731 <worker> int() can't convert non-string with explicit base
Traceback (most recent call last):
  File "build/bdist.linux-x86_64/egg/plaso/engine/worker.py", line 126, in _ParseFileEntryWithParser
    parser_object.Parse(self._parser_context, file_entry)
  File "build/bdist.linux-x86_64/egg/plaso/parsers/chrome_preferences.py", line 138, in Parse
    extensions_dict):
  File "build/bdist.linux-x86_64/egg/plaso/parsers/chrome_preferences.py", line 64, in _ExtractExtensionInstallationEvents
    install_time = int(extension.get(u'install_time', 0), 10)
TypeError: int() can't convert non-string with explicit base
```

The relevant bit being:

_install_time = int(__extension.get(u'install_time', 0)__, 10)
*_TypeError: int() can't convert non-string with explicit base***

This is something I should have caught... if there is no install time you get a 0 (an integer) back from the extension.get call. And the integer 0 cannot be casted to an integer, since it is already an integer.... better approach

install_time = int(extension.get(u'install_time', **u'0'**), 10)

title: log2timeline.py: workers remain alive
body:
RE: Git head 20141124

I initiated log2timeline.py yesterday against a partition.  I just checked its progress and it seems to be in an infinite loop.  I invoked log2timeline via:

> log2timeline.py -d --logfile plaso-debug.log --workers 4 --offset 411648 cu01c1.plasodb /mnt/imageCU01/ewf1

For the last 12+ hours I'm getting this in the debug output every 10 seconds:

> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,732 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Unable to connect to RPC socket to: Worker_0 at http://localhost:11784
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,733 [ERROR](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_0 [11784] is not functioning when it should be. Terminating it and removing from list.
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,734 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_0 [11784] is still alive.
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,736 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Unable to connect to RPC socket to: Worker_1 at http://localhost:11786
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,737 [ERROR](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_1 [11786] is not functioning when it should be. Terminating it and removing from list.
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,738 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_1 [11786] is still alive.
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,740 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Unable to connect to RPC socket to: Worker_2 at http://localhost:11788
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,740 [ERROR](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_2 [11788] is not functioning when it should be. Terminating it and removing from list.
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,742 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_2 [11788] is still alive.
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,743 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Unable to connect to RPC socket to: Worker_3 at http://localhost:11790
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,744 [ERROR](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_3 [11790] is not functioning when it should be. Terminating it and removing from list.
> 2014-11-26 15:26:48,745 [WARNING](MainProcess) PID:11761 <foreman> Process Worker_3 [11790] is still alive.

I went back and looked at the first occurrence and I don't see any relevant logs just before it started but I don't really know what I'm looking for.

I have the full debug.log, so let me know what I can provide.  

Likely an unrelated issue but before the infinite loop started I was getting this "ERROR" by the 10,000s of thousands, but it was more or less continuous for the whole time the image was processing:

Here it is with some context:

AttributeError: 'module' object has no attribute 'utc'

Which appears to be due to a circular dependency somewhere.

Workaround is stopping pytz from loading resource_stream from pkg_resources. In **init**.py for pytz, comment out these lines:
 try:
     from pkg_resources import resource_stream

     resource_stream = None

title: text_parser: PyparsingMultiLineTextParser invalid Unicode coercion
body:
Offending code in PyparsingMultiLineTextParser:

```
    """Fill the buffer."""
    if len(self._buffer) > self._buffer_size:
      return

    self._buffer += filehandle.read(self._buffer_size)

    # If a parser specifically indicates specific encoding we need
    # to handle the buffer as it is an unicode string.
    # If it fails we fail back to the original raw string.
    if self.encoding:
      try:
        buffer_decoded = self._buffer.decode(self.encoding)

        self._buffer = buffer_decoded
      except UnicodeDecodeError:
        pass
```

The issue:
- buffer starts out as a binary string
- buffer is converted into a Unicode string, which means that in the concat the newly read string is coerced into Unicode without the correct encoding

title: memory consumption

labels.name: enhancement
labels.description: New or improved functionality

body:
I've not been able to get in and debug precisely why, but memory consumption on processing Windows 7 machines is rather high.  On a 20-core, 20GB machine Plaso has 11 of 17 workers that are consuming more than 500MB apiece, two peaking out at 1.2GB and totaling 14GB.  It almost appears that workers are taking a page from Perl's book and being memory packrats - once they move on from parsing a given file they still hold on to a large amount of memory.

For the particular image I'm processing right now, I've had to kick up to the 20x20 resources, 10x10 was too small even for --workers=5.  Sorry I don't have more concrete info right now, but hopefully in the future consumption will drop a bit to make more reasonable machines useful.
